ce:section.ce:para:
Regarding the proposed base fluid, only a handful of studies have been performed on the thermophysical profile and the heat transfer performance of nanofluids based on aqueous solutions of propylene glycol at 10–30 wt%. For instance, Vallejo et al. [21] explored the thermophysical properties of mono B4C and TiB2 and hybrid TiB2:B4C nanofluids based on a propylene glycol:water 20:80 wt% mixture, namely, density, isobaric heat capacity, and thermal conductivity, as well as their rheological behaviour. Additionally, they also studied their surface tension and electrical conductivity. Nanoadditive concentration at 2 wt% was selected for the three nanofluids and results showed that B4C mono nanofluid present the highest improvements of thermal conductivity, 6%, and electrical conductivity, 70 times higher than the base fluid. It also showed the highest increase in dynamic viscosity up to 54%, while TiB2 mono nanofluid presented the maximum density increases, 1.5%, and heat capacity decreases, 1.7%. The hybrid nanofluid demonstrated intermediate values between those of the mono nanofluids for the studied properties but for dynamic viscosity increases, which were the lowest of all nanofluids up to 14%. Vallejo et al. 
                     [22] investigated the thermophysical profile PG:W 10:90 wt% mixture-based nanofluids at various ratios of hybrid nanoadditive (silver/graphene nanoplatelet with different functionalizations). Three total nanoadditive concentrations of 0.05, 0.1, and 1.0 wt% were analysed. Thermal conductivity showed practically no variations with respect to the base fluid while the maximum density increases up to 2.4% for the 1 wt% concentration of silver (only) nanoadditives. In their study, Newtonian behaviour was evidenced for all samples and viscosity increases lower than 9% were found. It was also noted that the presence of the silver nanoparticles produces higher increases in viscosity than the rising presence of graphene nanoplatelets. Kumar et al. [23] investigated the ultrasonic velocity (u), density (ρ), and viscosity (η) of zinc oxide-based nanofluids in a propylene glycol:water 10:90 vol% at different nanoparticle mass concentrations (0.02, 0.04, 0.06, 0.08, and 0.10 wt%). Then these experimental values were used to analyse various acoustic parameters such as adiabatic compressibility (βad
                     ), intermolecular free length (Lf
                     ), relaxation time (τ), acoustic impedance (Z), free volume (Vf
                     ), and attenuation coefficient (α/f2
                     ) to investigate molecular interactions. Increases in u, τ, Z, and α/f2
                      were found with increasing nanoparticle loading up to 0.04 wt% ZnO because of the molecular interactions among the nanoparticles and the base fluid (ZnO/PG:W). After that, these parameters showed a decrease with increasing nanoparticle mass concentration up to 0.08 wt% because of the molecular interactions augmentation between the nanoparticles and water (ZnO/W) and the nanoparticles and the propylene glycol (ZnO/PG) whereas decreasing molecular interactions between water and propylene glycol (W-PG). The values obtained for βad

                     , 
                     Vf
                     , and Lf
                      presented an opposite trend with the nanoparticle loading. Vallejo et al. [24] also previously analysed the temperature and concentration dependences on viscosity of dispersions of graphene nanoplatelets (from 0.25 wt% to 1.0 wt%) in PG:W, 30:70 and 10:90 wt%. Newtonian behaviour was observed over all the analysed concentrations, temperatures and shear rates, and dynamic viscosity increases up to 222% for the 1.0 wt% graphene dispersion in PG:W 30:70 wt% mixture at 283.15 K. Salamon et al. 
                     [25] studied the heat transfer characteristics of propylene glycol:water 30:70 based TiO2 nanofluids of 0.1 vol% and 0.3 vol% by varying the flow rate (between 3 and 6 l/min) at various temperatures (323, 333, 343, and 353 K). It was found that at higher operating temperature and higher flow, 0.3 vol% TiO2 nanofluid enhances the heat transfer rate by 8.5% compared to base fluid. Sundar et al. 
                     [26] experimentally determined the thermal conductivity and viscosity of nanodiamond nanofluids based on propylene glycol:water mixtures at different weight ratios (20:80, 40:60, and 60:40 wt%). Thermal conductivity increases of 18.8%, 16.8%, and 14.1% for 1.0 vol% of nanodiamond of 20:80, 40:60, and 60:40 PG:W nanofluids were found, respectively, while viscosity increases 1.55-times, 1.50-times, and 1.66-times for the same particle concentration and PG:W mixtures were obtained, respectively.
